%N A390914 a(n) = (n^(n - 1) + 1)^n.
%C A390914 Assume the radix-n numeral system. Let V_n(m) denote the radix-n constant congruence speed of m (see Appendix B of "A compact notation for peculiar properties characterizing integer tetration" in Links). Then, for each n >= 3, a(n) is a perfect power of exact order n (by Mihăilescu's Theorem) characterized by a radix-n constant congruence speed (exactly) equal to n. Thus, V_n(a(n)) = V_n((n^(n - 1) + 1)^n) = n holds for all n >= 3 (since, for any positive integer c multiple of n and t >= ord_n(c) + 2, V_n((n^(t - ord_n(c)) + 1)^c) = t holds, and thus n = t = c implies V_n((n^(t - ord_n(c)) + 1)^c) = V_n((n^(n - 1) + 1)^n) - see A379243 and "On the relation between perfect powers and tetration frozen digits" for a strict proof of the case n = 10).
%C A390914 On the other hand, as a consequence of the lifting-the-exponent lemma (LTE), one has V_2(a(2)) = n + 1 (instead of n).
%C A390914 In general (as long as n >= 2), the radix-n congruence speed of a(n) equals 2*V_n(a(n)) at height 1 and already stabilizes to its constant value, n or n + 1 (depending on whether n >= 3 or n = 2, respectively), from height 2 onward.
